  "text": "Apache Kafka uses a configuration management pattern based on the ConfigDef and ConfigKey classes for documenting and managing configuration parameters. This is not based on Java annotations as the task description suggests, but rather on a pattern of class-based configuration definitions.\n\n## Core Architecture\n\n**ConfigDef (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/common/config/ConfigDef.java)**: The primary class for specifying expected configurations. It contains a nested static class ConfigKey that represents individual configuration parameters. ConfigDef provides methods to define configurations with names, types, default values, documentation, validation logic, groups, ordering, and display information.\n\n**ConfigKey (nested in ConfigDef.java)**: A static inner class that encapsulates all metadata for a single configuration key, including: name, type (STRING, INT, LONG, DOUBLE, BOOLEAN, LIST, CLASS, PASSWORD), documentation, defaultValue, validator, importance (HIGH, MEDIUM, LOW), group, orderInGroup, width, displayName, dependents, recommender, internalConfig flag, and alternativeString.\n\n**AbstractConfig (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/common/config/AbstractConfig.java)**: A base class that provides convenient methods for accessing configuration values. It holds a ConfigDef definition instance and provides methods like typeOf() and documentationOf() that retrieve metadata about configuration keys from the embedded ConfigDef.\n\n## Configuration Classes\n\nThe pattern is extensively used throughout Kafka across multiple modules:\n\n**Client Module**: AdminClientConfig, ConsumerConfig, ProducerConfig provide configuration for admin, consumer, and producer clients respectively.\n\n**Connect Module**: TaskConfig, WorkerConfig, ConnectorConfig, SourceConnectorConfig, SinkConnectorConfig, DistributedConfig, RestServerConfig, ConverterConfig define configurations for Kafka Connect components.\n\n**Mirror Module**: MirrorClientConfig, MirrorMakerConfig, MirrorConnectorConfig, MirrorCheckpointConfig, MirrorSourceConfig manage Mirror Maker configurations.\n\n**Streams Module**: StreamsConfig and AssignmentConfigs configure Kafka Streams applications.\n\n**Server Module**: ServerConfigs, AbstractKafkaConfig, ClientMetricsConfigs define broker-level configurations.\n\n**Other Modules**: GroupConfig manages consumer group configurations, LogConfig manages log-level configurations.\n\n## Utility and REST Support\n\nConfigUtils provides utility methods for working with ConfigDef instances. AbstractHerder and ConnectorConfig use ConfigKey for configuration conversion and enrichment. ConfigKeyInfo (in connect/runtime/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/connect/runtime/rest/entities/) provides a REST-friendly representation of ConfigKey metadata. KafkaConfigSchema manages the complete configuration schema for the Kafka broker.\n\nThe pattern demonstrates a comprehensive configuration management system where each configuration parameter is formally documented with type information, validation rules, importance levels, and cross-references, enabling both programmatic configuration validation and automated documentation generation."
}

